tool.help:
Do you have work with web archives? Web ARchive Container (WARC) files contained archived web data and their accompanying metadata.

If you have a gzipped WARC and want to know what is in it, you can use warcio index. 

warcio index accepts a WARC file and produces an index of the contents of the WARC file in line-delimited JSON.

For example, an index for a simple WARC file would look as follows:

{"offset": "0", "warc-type": "warcinfo"}
{"offset": "333", "warc-type": "response", "warc-target-uri": "http://example.com?example=1"}
{"offset": "1376", "warc-type": "request", "warc-target-uri": "http://example.com?example=1"}
{"offset": "1864", "warc-type": "revisit", "warc-target-uri": "http://example.com?example=1"}
{"offset": "2417", "warc-type": "request", "warc-target-uri": "http://example.com?example=1"}
{"offset": "2907", "warc-type": "response", "warc-target-uri": "http://www.iana.org/domains/example"} 

Each line represents the contents of a location in the WARC file, which begins at the byte offset indicate in the "offset" field.

The URL to the remote resource that is archived in the WARC file is indicated in the "warc-target-uri" field.

WARC files contain data of different types, including whether archived data relates to a HTTP request, a HTTP response, or something else. 
This is indicated in the "warc-type" field.

Input: A gzipped WARC file which you would like to explore the contents of
Output: An index of the contents of the inputted WARC file in line-delimited JSON
